- "Predominant middle-class income" refers to areas where the most common income category is the middle range, which is between $50,000 and $100,000;
- "Relatively low poverty rate" means the average poverty rate is less than 15%;
- "Latest data" refers to the most recent year of data available for each geographic area.

- "Higher-than-average access" implies the dataset has more access events compared to the average of all datasets.;
- "High data quality" means the dataset has average quality metrics (Accuracy, Completeness, Consistency) all above 0.9, indicating reliable and trustworthy data.;
- "Multiple tags" suggests the dataset is well-categorized with more than 2 tags.;
- "Substantial file sizes" indicates the dataset contains more than one file with a combined size greater than 100 MB.;

- The `geoid` is a unique identifier for each geographic location;
- The `m_income` represents the median household income for a given geographic location;
- The `location` refers to the name of the geographic area.

- `inc_group_name` represents the name of the income group;
- `m_income` is the median household income;
- `quality_value` is a metric that measures the quality of the data;
- The query groups the data by income group and calculates the minimum median income and the average data quality for each group;
- The results are ordered alphabetically by income group name.

- "Top 3 highest median household incomes" refers to the datasets ranked 1, 2, and 3 by median household income within each geographic location;
- "Average total income" is the sum of the top 3 median household incomes divided by the number of locations;
- "Overall average median household income" is the average of median household incomes across all datasets.

- `avg_median_income` represents the average median household income for a given state and county;
- `avg_white_population` represents the average percentage of the white population in a given state and county;
- `state_rank` indicates the ranking of a county within its state based on average median income;
- `county_rank` indicates the ranking of a county within itself based on average median income.

- Median owner-occupied housing value refers to the middle value of the distribution of home values for properties that are owner-occupied;
- The year 2020 is a specific time frame used to filter the data;
- "Jewels in the crown" is a metaphorical expression used to highlight the top-performing cities.

- "majority of the population is white" refers to the average percentage of the white population being greater than 50%;
- "golden threshold" refers to an average median household income greater than $50,000;
- "average household wealth" is represented by the average median household income.

- 'High median household incomes' refers to areas where the average income is significantly higher than the general population;
- 'Valuable homes' refers to areas with high median owner-occupied housing values;
- 'Drawing the attention of many visitors' means that these areas have datasets that have been accessed more than 10 times.

- "higher-than-average median household income" refers to locations where the average median household income is greater than the overall average median household income in the dataset;
- "significant white population" implies a notable percentage of the population identified as white;
- "geographic locations" are identified by their names in the `location` column.

- "The majority of the population is white" refers to `perc_white > 50`;
- "Fewer than one in ten live below the poverty line" refers to `perc_poverty < 10`;
- "Surpasses the national average" refers to `AVG(T1.m_income) > (SELECT AVG(m_income) FROM datasets)`;
- "Shine with an average median household income" refers to the average median household income being higher than the overall average.

- "recent years" refers to years after 2010;
- "higher median incomes" refers to median incomes greater than 50,000;
- "multiple data sources and versions" means there are more than one distinct data source and more than one distinct version.

- "Higher average median income" refers to an average median income greater than 50,000;
- "Lower poverty rates" refers to an average percentage of the population below the poverty level less than 20%;
- "Past decade" refers to the years between 2010 and 2020.

- 'Prosperity' refers to the average percentage of households with income above $200,000;
- 'The golden state' is a nickname for California;
- 'Exceeds a tenth' means the average percentage is greater than 10%.

- "Top 3 income groups" refers to the highest median household incomes within each geographic location;
- "Geographic location" is identified by the `geoid` and `location` columns;
- "Income group" is identified by the `inc_group_name` column.

- 'most valuable gem' refers to the dataset with the highest average median income and average data quality;
- 'shining with the highest average median income' means the dataset has the highest average median income;
- 'purest data quality' means the dataset has the highest average data quality.

- 'Median household income' is a measure of the average household income in a geographic area;
- 'Median rent' is the middle value of rent paid by households in a geographic area;
- The `geoid` is a unique identifier for geographic locations in the database.
